widgets_values:
Use Fast Groups Bypasser (rgthree) to enable / disable IP Adpater 1 (style) & 2 (reference), ControlNet 1 & 2, Tiled Diffusion and Post-process effects group.

Use Enable toggles in the top row to enable / disable individual Style and Reference IP adapters, as well as ControlNet 1 and 2. 

To enable individual source file usage for Style, Reference and both ControlNets, expand (if it's in the collapsed state) the purple-colored Image group node under the corresponding component, drag and drop the image into it and turn True the yellow Use image toggle above. By default, the workflow will use the main source image for each component.

To enable individual mask file usage for Reference and ControlNet 1, expand (if collapsed), then right click on the group node under the corresponding Image group node and select Bypass to unblock it. Next, drag and drop the image into the purple-colored mask image group node. The mask images should be in RGB format, with each channel representing the same grayscale mask. Should the mask need to be inverted, use the bottom widget of the (expanded) mask image group node.   

Resolution Multiplier (RM): a factor to increase or decrease image resolution during generation (default: 1). Setting it to values above 1 can result in adding extra detail in the output, by the price of longer computing times and higher chances of distortions and checkpoint hallucinations. Recommended values between 1.2 and 2.0. 

Setting RM to values below 1.0 will result in scaling down of the image before generation. This can help to avoid distortions (most commonly, in human figures) in the output due to the current input resolution being higher than the checkpoint's native one, when a denoise value above 0.3-0.4 is used. Can be useful only for input resolutions between 1.2-2.5K, for larger images use Tile ControlNet to prevent distortions and loss of coherence. 

After generation, the image will be resized back to the original pixel dimensions, unless Upscale mode was turned on. The RM feature uses Lanzcos method for resizing, hence the range limit of 0.5-2.0. 

Upscale mode: turn on, if you want the image to remain upscaled after generation (ignored for RM values below 1.0).

HDR-enhancing with the HDR intensity widget at the far right: values from 0 (disable, default) to 1 (max); 0.5 recommended for the best effect. Options to enhance contrast and color are also available in the LayerFilter: HDR Effects node the widget is connected to.

Sharpening/softening with the Sharpen strength widget at the far right: values from -0.3 (soften) to 1 (max sharpen), with 0 as the default; 0.3 might be a good choice to try. For a more nuanced effect, various options are available in the Image Smart Sharpen node connected to the widget.

Color-matching with the Color matching degree widget at the far right: values from 0 (disable, default) to 1 (max); 0.9 recommended for the best effect.
